<TEXT>
a jury thursday recommended execution 
for a convict who murdered his exwife while on prison furlough 
last year 
alan l matheney 39 stood quietly as lake county superior 
court judge james e letsinger read the recommendation of death in 
the electric chair letsinger who must make the final decision 
set sentencing for may 4 
the same jury wednesday rejected matheneys insanity defense and 
convicted him of murder and burglary in the march 4 1989 beating 
death of lisa marie bianco 
the jury deliberated for more than four hours thursday before 
issuing a recommendation had jurors not elected to recommend 
death they could have urged a prison sentence of up to 60 years 
for murder and 20 years for burglary 
matheneys mother martha matheney showed no reaction to the 
decision as she sat in the back row of the courtroom 
the victims father eugene bianco said he was pleased its 
a just sentence for the crime he committed bianco said i hope 
it doesnt drag on for years 
a death sentence would automatically be appealed to the state 
supreme court 
bianco said his grandchildren still have nightmares about the 
night matheney broke into their home armed with an unloaded 
shotgun and threatened their mother matheney chased ms bianco 
into the street and beat her outside a neighbors home 
the kids miss their mother more and they wish mr matheney 
was no longer their father bianco said 
letsinger extended a gag order on attorneys until sentencing 
st joseph county prosecutor michael p barnes cited the order and 
declined to comment 
defense attorney scott l king however held a brief news 
conference outside the courthouse and said he would argue for a 
prison term 
the state proved two circumstances burglary and lying in wait 
to justify the death penalty county deputy prosecutor john d 
krisor said earlier 
the slaying sparked a furor over officials failure to notify 
ms bianco 29 of the furlough for matheney who had been serving 
an eightyear sentence for assaulting her in 1987 the states 
furlough program was suspended and later reinstated with tightened 
restrictions 
</TEXT>
