<TEXT>
the soviet union for the first time has admitted 
responsibility for the massacre of thousands of polish prisoners in 
the katyn forest during world war ii the british broadcasting 
corp reported friday 
until now the soviet union has blamed the 1940 massacre of 
15000 polish army officers and soldiers near the western town 
smolensk on nazi germany 
the formal admission of guilt coincides with the threeday state 
visit of polish president wojciech jaruzelski who is scheduled to 
visit katyn saturday the acknowledgement of responsibility for the 
slaying has been one of the conditions for improvement in relations 
between poland and the soviet union 
a bbc world service radio news bulletin quoted radio moscow as 
saying recently discovered documents determined the crime was 
carried out by the soviet nkvd predecessors of the kgb secret 
police 
the bbc quoted the official radio as describing the massacre as 
one of the worst outrages of the stalinist era in the soviet union 
and said radio moscow expressed deep regret for the atrocity 
the katyn area where the bodies of more than 4000 polish 
offiders were found in a mass grave changed hands as the war 
progressed first being under soviet control and then nazi control 
the victims were prisoners of war captured in the nazisoviet 
partition of poland at the start of the war the poles had been 
interned after the soviets invaded poland in 1939 
the killings eliminated some of most talented officers in 
poland and for years has been a source of deep resentment for 
poles who until august were under communist rule the government is 
now under rule of the solidarity tradue union movement 
the crime was first disclosed in 1943 by the nazis who 
attributed it to the nkvd 
</TEXT>
