<DOCNO> AP900412-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
culture minister jack lang has denounced a new us 
immigration rule saying it will soon be easier for foreign artists 
and performers to work in moscow than new york 
lang was referring to a regulation which took effect feb 26 
requiring foreign artists who wish to work temporarily in the 
united states to show proof of their commercial success or 
international fame to obtain the desirable h1 visa 
under the new rule vincent van gogh would be denied access to 
american territory lang told reporters at a news conference 
the ruling means that as far as cultural exchange is 
concerned moscow is more accessible than los angeles or new 
york he said 
a second category of visas called h2s are issued on a regular 
basis to ordinary alien workers but lang said the procedure for 
obtaining them is much slower and more complicated making it 
difficult for performers to arrange their schedules 
the us embassy in paris issued a statement saying no laws 
concerning h1 or h2 have been changed 
the new regulations issued on feb 26 were simply a 
clarification of existing laws there has been a long tradition of 
cultural exchange between france and the united states and we trust 
that a continuing spirit of cooperation and mutual respect will 
resolve any problems that may arise the statement said 
in a recent commentary in billboard magazine american 
immigration lawyer jeffrey gabel said there were fears in the 
united states that the new rule would hinder foreign artists who 
are not superstars 
the effects of this action could narrow the chances of foreign 
artists and entertainers and their support staffs to enter the 
united states gabel wrote 
lang cited several examples of artists famous in france but 
not superstars in the minds of us immigration officers who have 
been denied h1 visas 
they include film maker elie chouraqui and the rock group 
niagara which was forced to cancel performances in baltimore 
chicago and washington this year after failing to get visas 
lang said niagaras musicians were asked by immigration 
officials to show proof of their usefulness to the american 
public 
chouraqui lang said received a visa only after weeks of 
waiting and the intervention of lang paris mayor jacques chirac 
and finally jack valenti president of the motion picture 
association of america 
lang called the new rule unacceptable and urged the united 
states to modify it as quickly as possible to ensure the free 
circulation of artists worldwide 
in france all artists are welcome he said during tuesdays 
news conference adding that french work permits for foreign 
artists are simple rapid certain free and almost automatic 
lang said he would discuss the issue with his colleagues at the 
may 13 meeting of european cabinet ministers he urged the 
formation of a francoamerican committee of artists to promote 
freedom of movement 
</TEXT>
