<TEXT>
democrat ann richards overcame allegations of 
drug abuse to win the gubernatorial nomination in texas but 
analysts say voters can be fickle about judging politicians with 
drugs in their past 
age sex and the drug of choice all may have something to do 
with it they say and so can the candidates opponent 
accusations of drug abuse and related character attacks so 
dominated the fourweek texas gubernatorial runoff between ms 
richards and state attorney general jim mattox that one commentator 
said the contest had sunk from the gutters to the sewers 
but the same issue created few ripples in massachusetts where 
11 politicians last month admitted they had tried marijuana and 
similar admissions appeared to play no role in the losing 1988 
presidential campaigns of democrats bruce babbitt and al gore 
just last week the senate approved timothy ryan as the nations 
chief savings and loan regulator after senators displayed little 
concern that he had tried marijuana and cocaine while in law school 
in texas mattox pursued ms richards relentlessly on the drug 
issue after she refused to say whether she had used illegal drugs 
did she use marijuana or something worse like cocaine not 
as a college kid but as a 47yearold elected official sworn to 
uphold the law mattox asked in one television ad later he 
alleged outright that ms richards the state treasurer once had a 
cocaine addiction but by the end he too was fighting off drug 
use allegations 
still to be seen is whether the drug issue will dog richards in 
her general election contest against republican clayton williams 
analysts say there are many potential difficulties starting with 
her age at 56 she is substantially older than the generation 
usually associated with and excused for experimental drug use 
anything you did before 25 is to be forgiven even if it was 
only 10 years ago said democratic consultant tony podesta but 
if you indulged your drug fantasies when you were 47 it sounds a 
lot different 
the issue also is harder to overcome for women analysts said 
because people generally tolerate freewheeling behavior more easily 
in men than in women in ms richards case they note the 
allegations also contrast sharply with the grandmotherly image she 
tried to project in her ads 
the particular drug at issue also matters with voters 
william schneider a political analyst at the american 
enterprise institute said occasional or infrequent marijuana use 
if not forgiven is at least understood by voters but cocaine 
is a different story 
if it was only marijuana she would have said so schneider 
said richards a recovering alcoholic told voters she had used no 
moodaltering chemicals in the past 10 years but refused to 
say what if any drugs she had used previously 
ms richards won anyway but analysts said the texas race was a 
flawed test of whether voters will be forgiving of past drug use 
charles cook editor of cooks political report cited mattoxs 
attackdog style his failure to release his income tax returns and 
the lastminute allegations that he had smoked marijuana 
it wasnt a situation where you had allegations about drug use 
by one candidate and the other candidate seemed pure as the driven 
snow cook said 
both candidates ended up with high negatives because of the 
drug issue said jill buckley a democratic communications 
consultant 
buckley and others said voters found ms richards the less 
offensive candidate because she started the race with a reputation 
for decency and there was a sense she was being unfairly hammered 
on drugs 
in contrast with texas ryans law school experiments with 
marijuana and cocaine recounted in a leaked fbi report were all 
but ignored when the senate confirmed him last week to head the 
treasury departments office of thrift supervision 
senators were quick to condemn the leak and defend the nominee 
mostly on the grounds of his age which is 44 
whatever ryan did ended 17 years ago said sen bob dole 
rkan if he is to be held up to that standard then we are going 
to wipe out a generation of men and women who are about that age 
who may have experimented at one time or another with some type of 
drug 
podesta said some of the same dynamics were at work in 
massachusetts when a crowd of politicians including a senator 
two congressmen and five candidates for state office confessed to 
past dalliances with drugs the public appeared to respond with a 
mass so what 
you have a younger generation of politicians a more liberal 
social atmosphere heavily influenced by the academic community 
podesta said 
