<TEXT>
researchers have uncovered details of a gene 
from a magnolia tree that lived in idaho about 20 million years 
ago by far the oldest plant or animal tissue ever to yield that 
information 
the genetic material came from leaf samples that were 
exceptionally well preserved by an ancient lake researchers 
reported today in the british journal nature 
such analysis can shed light on the relationships between 
extinct species and their presentday descendants helping 
researchers construct the scientific equivalent of family trees 
the new report demonstrates an opportunity to take a new 
technology and apply it to the study of classical problems in 
biology said study coauthor michael clegg of the university of 
california at riverside 
he did the work with postdoctoral student edward golenberg and 
others at the university and scientists at the university of 
georgia in athens the university of idaho in moscow and the dnax 
research institute in palo alto calif 
the leaf samples from an excavation in the panhandle area of 
northern idaho were from 17 million to 20 million years old 
the oldest material that previously had yielded to similar 
genetic analysis was human brain tissue about 7000 years old 
recovered from a bog in florida clegg said in a recent telephone 
interview 
genetic material called deoxyribonucleic acid or dna was 
extracted from leaf samples and a part of it was duplicated 
repeatedly using a technique called polymerase chain reaction 
researchers determined its chemical makeup and found that the dna 
was from a gene that acted as a blueprint for part of a particular 
plant protein 
the fact that we could do it once probably means it can be 
done again with materials from other sites clegg said 
the leaf samples were exceptionally well preserved having 
fallen into a cold lake that rapidly silted in the cold and the 
low amounts of oxygen available helped preserve the leaves he said 
it is unclear how many other sites could offer such 
wellpreserved specimens for dna analysis he said 
but the new report suggests the idaho site itself may provide 
an extraordinarily wellpreserved assemblage of fossils that 
could yield an abundance of information much like the famed la 
brea pits said karl niklas botany professor at cornell university 
in ithaca 
the la brea pits in los angeles are one of the worlds richest 
known sources of ice age fossils 
clegg said dna work has begun with other leaves from the site 
the site contained remnants of more than 100 species of plants 
perhaps half were preserved in somewhat the same way as the 
magnolia leaves and dna might be recovered from some of them said 
study coauthor charles smiley of the university of idaho 
the site also contained 30 to 40 kinds of insects some of which 
still had their original colors and four kinds of fish he said 
but it is unclear what their potential for dna analysis would be 
he said 
niklas said that if other remains from the same site could be 
made to reveal genetic details it would reveal an unique slice 
through time based on dna analysis thats an extremely 
exciting possibility 
</TEXT>
