<TEXT>
a projected increase of up to 50 percent in 
average global concentrations of the pollutant ozone over the next 
30 years would make little difference in us cities with an ozone 
problem a scientist says 
about 100 areas in the united states fail to meet federal 
standards for ozone levels including essentially all major cities 
according to the us environmental protection agency 
but the projected global average increase would have only a 
minor impact on american cities because local pollution is the main 
cause of their ozone troubles said scientist brian ridley of the 
national center for atmospheric research in boulder colo 
ozone is a form of oxygen that plays a jekyllandhyde role in 
the atmosphere at high altitudes it shields earth from solar rays 
that can promote skin cancer but near the earths surface it is a 
pollutant that irritates sensitive lung tissues and harms crops 
lowaltitude ozone is created by nitrogen oxides and 
hydrocarbons that come from automobile exhaust and industrial 
sources 
ridley was commenting on a study in todays issue of the british 
journal nature that projected an increase of 21 percent to 50 
percent in average global levels of lowaltitude ozone by the year 
2020 
he also cautioned that such projections are uncertain because of 
lack of scientific knowledge about such factors as the distribution 
of nitrogen oxides in the atmosphere 
the increase dealt with concentrations at the earths surface 
over land only study coauthor adrian hough said in an interview 
he and richard derwent did the projections at the harwell 
laboratory in didcot england 
hough said local ozone control measures may have to be more 
stringent if the projected increase takes place because local 
ozone readings reflect this background level as well as local 
pollution 
one projection focused on latitudes typical of the central 
united states it found a rise in annual averages from about 30 
parts per billion today to perhaps 35 parts or 45 parts per billion 
in the year 2020 hough said 
under epa criteria an area fails to comply with the ozone 
standard if it exceeds 120 parts per billion for more than an 
average of once a year over a threeyear period 
hough said the main factor behind the calculated rise in overall 
global ozone is increased emissions from industrialization and 
automobile use in developing nations 
</TEXT>
