<TEXT>
the agriculture department says smallscale 
farmers who have woodlots on their property sometimes dont realize 
that money does grow on trees 
and if you want to start from scratch and wait 15 to 50 years 
depending on the region newly planted trees eventually can return 
a profit 
experts say at least 6 million people own woodlots averaging 40 
to 50 acres they make up about onethird of the nations 348 
million acres of private timberland 
the woodlot possibilities are described in a fact sheet by the 
office for smallscale agriculture which is operated by usdas 
cooperative state research service 
previous topics have included sheep goats mushrooms foliage 
plants herbs wildflowers herbs specialty vegetables and 
exotic livestock such as ostriches llamas alpacas water 
buffalo and european fallow deer 
many can improve their land management the report said 
this fact sheet is intended mainly for them rather than for 
others who may want to try to get into the business 
but there are newcomers to woodlot management including many 
farmers who are planting trees on more than 2 million acres under 
the governments conservation reserve program 
the program offers initial planting assistance and annual rental 
payments to farmers who agree to take highly erodible cropland from 
production for 10 years and protect it with grass and trees 
a number of other federal and state programs along with private 
efforts are directed at woodlot improvements 
most woodlot farmers dont fully manage their operations and 
timber growth generally reaches only 50 percent to 60 percent of 
potential the report said good management means getting each acre 
to produce the maximum annual growth possible and to replace 
harvested trees 
owners with already established woodlots often have immediate 
income potential the report said sometimes however the 
return covers decades 
one example cited by the usda agency was reported in the 
american tree farmer official publication of the american tree 
farm system which has certified 65000 tree farmers on 91 million 
acres 
nels hanson president of the washington farm forestry 
association told about a couple lula and vern johnson who bought 
their 40acre washington farm for 102 an acre including a 
sixacre patch of 40yearold douglas fir trees 
between 1949 and 1987 as money was needed to clear and plant 
understocked areas they logged and thinned the stand when the 
stand of douglas fir was sold to the weyerhaeuser co in 1988 it 
had 660000 boardfeet of lumber and brought nearly 382 per 
thousand or 252000 
not everyone can find a timber investment to match that the 
report said 
for those wanting to start a longterm timber program unused 
areas along streams or creeks often good sites the exact species 
of trees would depend on local growing conditions and advice from 
foresters 
the south produces salable lumber products in 15 to 25 
years the report said in the north and west it usually takes 
30 to 50 years in the south final harvests usually take place in 
30 to 40 years and in the north and west about 60 to 80 years 
the report added fairly intensive management is required to 
produce sawlogs in those time frames 
