infiltrated the merc and the chicago board of trade in a probe of 
suspected fraud fortyeight people mostly traders were indicted 
last summer 
we believe you will find the session both interesting and 
stimulating and trust you will leave the session with much to 
think about merc officials said in a letter to members last week 
the board of trade already has started a mandatory ethics 
session for all new members said spokesman michael oconnell 
he said bot officials also are working with the center for 
ethics and corporate policy in chicago to create an course that 
could include other members as well 
james oliff second vice president of the mercs board of 
governors said anyone who trades at the merc must take the new 
course he said they will first be given a definition of what 
ethics is all about 
basically we want to impress upon our members that in 
addition to looking at rules that there are other actions that 
should govern their conduct and thats ethical behavior he said 
they are guardians of the exchange as a financial institution as 
well as guardians of themselves 
merc members will be told the consequences of violating rules 
and will be shown hypothetical situations involving questionable 
trading practices oliff said 
the class is being offered free after trading hours and will 
be taught by faculty at chicagokent college of law 
