equipment ordered by iraq and impounded at an 
english port could be used as a barrel of a large artillery gun 
the customs and excise office said today 
arms experts said a gun of the size seized by customs 
130feetlong with a 40inch bore could fire nuclear or chemical 
warheads as far as tehran or tel aviv each within 350 miles of 
iraqs borders 
the manufacturer and the iraqi government insisted that the 
equipment was a pipe intended for use in a petrochemical plant 
customs officers seized the equipment tuesday night and the 
agency said it was investigating whether there had been a violation 
of the british embargo on arms shipments to iraq 
we are now satisfied that this equipment is covered by the 
munitions list of the export of goods control order 1989 customs 
chief douglas tweddle said this afternoon 
there is no question it could be used as a barrel of a large 
artillery gun to fire a projectile of some considerable size it is 
definitely subject to export licensing controls 
the goods are now seized investigations will continue to 
prove intent and to establish whether offenses have been 
committed tweddle said 
he said the guns capability was confirmed by ministry of 
defense experts who inspected the cargo today on the docks at 
middlesbrough in northeastern england 
