a latestarting easter selling season and a 
continuing auto slump combined to push march retail sales down for 
the second straight month the government said thursday 
sales fell 06 percent to a seasonally adjusted 1486 billion 
after a 03 percent drop in february the commerce department 
reported 
the drop was the steepest in five months and marked the first 
backtoback sales slump since october and november 1986 only food 
stores posted higher sales 
consumers seem to be much more wary of spending money than 
they had been said economist s jay levy of levy economic 
forecasts in chappaqua ny with home prices in many areas of 
the country falling i think this gives pause to many people 
stock prices rose immediately after the reports release the 
new indication of continued sluggish economic growth suggested less 
upward pressure on interest rates than had been feared lately 
however analysts pointed to a number of mitigating factors that 
softened the news 
february sales originally reported as falling 09 percent and 
later revised to a minus 08 percent were revised upward again 
this time sharply 
both months followed a very strong january increase of 28 
percent 
easter this year falls three weeks later than it did last year 
some clothing and department store sales that would have occurred 
in march with an earlier easter were thus shifted to april 
march was weak but to me it was a deceptive weakness said 
economist robert g dederick of northern trust co its another 
one of those moreofthesame reports the consumer is sort of 
doing what the economy is doing hes plodding ahead but not in a 
straight line 
sales in the first three months of the year were up 55 percent 
from the same period of 1989 however some of the gain was 
attributed to unseasonably mild weather and auto discounting in 
january 
i think first quarter sales borrowed from the spring and 
that could show up in depressing the april number said 
economist maury n harris of paine webber inc 
retail sales which account for about a third of all economic 
activity are closely watched as a barometer of economic health 
in recent months consumer demand particularly for highpriced 
items such as autos has been weakened by the federal reserve 
boards policy of using high interest rates to dampen demand and 
consequently inflationary pressures 
car dealers and auto parts stores reported their fifth sales 
decline in six months sales totaled 307 billion in march down 
14 percent after a 65 percent drop in february 
excluding the volatile auto sector sales fell 04 percent in 
march after strong gains of 15 percent in february and 11 percent 
in january 
sales of durable goods big ticket items expected to last 
three or more years slumped 08 percent in march after a 27 
percent drop a month earlier sales of nondurable goods fell 05 
percent after rising 11 percent in february 
in other sectors march sales fell 1 percent at department and 
other general merchandise stores 05 percent at clothing stores 
01 percent at furniture outlets 08 percent at building supply 
hardware and garden stores 17 percent at gasoline stations 15 
percent at restaurants and bars and 09 percent at drug stores 
they rose 02 percent at food stores 
