<TEXT>
opponents of a state welfare experiment 
that cuts benefits for families whose teenagers play hooky are 
pressuring the government to withdraw its permission for the 
program 
but gov tommy g thompson who introduced the learnfare program 
two years ago wants to expand the program to include elementary 
school children 
hes also considering plans that would refuse to increase 
benefits to single mothers who have more children while on welfare 
rolls and would allow welfare recipients to work more than 100 
hours a month and still receive benefits 
we think wisconsin deserves it said thompson a republican 
who is up for reelection this fall wisconsin is recognized as a 
leader in welfare reform and well continue to move forward 
while thompson forges ahead with the experiments church and 
social groups are organizing their opposition to learnfare saying 
the state is moving too fast with programs that penalize the poor 
learnfare cuts aid to families with dependent children benefits 
to families whose teenagers skip school without an excuse afdc 
benefits in wisconsin range from 249 to 983 a month depending on 
family size 
learnfare cuts those benefits by 20 to 192 a month for each 
month a familys child or children fail to regularly attend school 
food stamps and other public assistance are not affected 
about 2200 of the estimated 30000 teenagers whose families 
receive afdc have been penalized each month most are in the 
milwaukee area 
supporters such as thompson argue that education is the first 
step to breaking the cycle of welfare dependency and that learnfare 
encourages students to stay in school 
opponents point to a recent study conducted by university of 
wisconsinmilwaukee that showed only 28 percent of children whose 
families were punished under learnfare returned to school and 
remained there for at least two months 
an earlier analysis by the state had estimated that about 70 
percent of the violators returned to school 
carol croce executive director of the wisconsin nutrition 
program a madisonbased advocacy group said learnfare unfairly 
sanctions parents and doesnt get at why the kid is missing 
school by taking away that money youre plunging them further 
into poverty 
ms croces group is among nearly 20 church and community 
organizations statewide that have jointly asked us secretary of 
health and human services louis sullivan to abolish learnfare on 
the grounds that it causes families undue hardship 
others joining in include the milwaukee catholic archdiocese 
the milwaukee urban league the naacp the league of women voters 
and the national association of social workers 
we all came to the realization after the release of the 
uwmilwaukee study that all of our worst fears had been justified 
that learnfare harms families who are in distress said mike 
soika a spokesman for the milwaukee catholic archdiocese 
in washington two wisconsin democrats sen herbert h kohl and 
rep jim moody cautioned sullivan not to grant thompson permission 
to expand the program until more statistics are compiled 
it may be premature to grant a waiver for a program that 
hasnt proved its effectiveness said marcus kunian a spokesman 
for moody 
thompsons request to expand learnfare remains under 
consideration and a final decision has not been made said david 
siegel spokesman for the family support administration of the us 
department of health and social services 
on a national level the american public welfare association a 
washingtonbased professional organization for social workers 
considered including a learnfare model program in proposed 1986 
welfare changes but decided against taking a position 
some felt it was too punitive said kathy patterson 
spokeswoman for the association the people we represent are very 
much divided on the learnfare model 
ms patterson said many states certainly are looking with 
interest at learnfare and await more comprehensive studies of it 
whether or not thompson succeeds in expanding learnfare 
opposition to the program wont stop ms croce said well work 
to make the administration accountable she said 
