<TEXT>
maoist guerrillas attacked a base built by the 
us government as a staging ground for antidrug operations 
sparking a battle involving american civilians and peruvian police 
us officials said thursday 
no americans or peruvian police were killed or wounded in the 
hourlong battle saturday a us embassy spokesman said base 
personnel found no rebel bodies but that police believed several 
dead rebels may have been carried off after the predawn battle 
he said between 40 and 60 guerrillas attacked the base with 
small arms and grenade launchers 
it was the first attack on the new 3 million base in santa 
lucia 265 northeast of lima the base is a staging ground for 
antidrug operations in perus cocarich upper huallaga valley 
the valley is a stronghold of the maoist shining path rebels 
drug smugglers pay the rebels to operate in the area 
the guerrillas say they are defending the interests of peasant 
coca farmers from abuses by drug traffickers and the police 
the spokesman who asked that his name not be used for security 
reasons said us antidrug personnel working in the area have 
been fired on in the past although this was the biggest attack to 
date 
peruvian police sources said us helicopters were called in to 
repel a december guerrilla attack against a police post in nuevo 
progresso a town about six miles from the base embassy officials 
denied the report at the time 
an american pilot was wounded in the leg when his helicopter was 
fired on during an operation in february 1989 that prompted the 
withdrawal of us personnel from the valley until the fortified 
santa lucia base was finished in september 
us law prohibits american personnel or equipment from being 
used against guerrillas except when they are attacked during 
antidrug operations 
about 30 americans have worked out of the base since september 
they include federal drug enforcement administration agents and 
civilian helicopter pilots and mechanics working for a private 
company under contract to the us state department 
normally about 500 people are stationed there including 
peruvian police rangers and civilian eradication workers but the 
