three clerical workers at the nations 
secondlargest public employee union charged in a federal suit 
thursday that the union had discriminated against blacks in its 
hiring and promotion decisions 
the suit filed in us district court alleged that the 
american federation of state county and municipal employees had 
violated federal civil rights laws by engaging in deliberate and 
systematic employment practices that discriminate against blacks 
afscmes employment practices are sound and within the law 
said bob harman a spokesman for the 125million member union he 
declined further comment until lawyers had reviewed the case about 
17 percent of the unions rankandfile members are black the 
union said 
the suit comes at a time when the american labor movement 
facing declining membership in recent years is trying to court 
blacks and women to rebuild strength 
the suit charged that afscme through the acts and omissions 
of its overwhelmingly white supervisory work force discriminated 
against blacks in decisions involving hiring assignments 
promotion compensation and discipline 
furthermore the suit alleged white supervisors harassed and 
disciplined blacks who complained about discriminatory practices 
the suit said that in 1988 blacks made up about 32 percent of 
the work force at the unions washington headquarters but that 
there were no black department heads last year only one of 14 
department heads was black it said 
blacks are confined to lowerlevel jobs in the organization the 
suit also contends while blacks had only 15 percent of the jobs 
paying more than 50000 a year in 1989 they held 47 percent of 
the positions in the unions four lowest pay grades the suit said 
the three black workers who filed the suit are mary craft and 
mary maynard office assistants at the unions washington 
headquarters and jean brown a secretary in the unions baltimore 
field office the three women all maryland residents represent 
former current and future black job applicants and employees 
dating back to february 1984 
the suit seeks back pay promotions and reclassifications for 
those blacks and compensatory and punitive damages in amounts to be 
determined at trial 
the national education association is the only public employee 
union with more members than afscme 
