<TEXT>
at what they billed as their largest 
congress ever gypsies from 27 countries demanded respect for their 
culture and an end to the stereotypes that have long seen them 
scorned as thieving fortunetellers 
the weeklong meeting of some 300 delegates ended wednesday with 
the appeals from the worldwide wanderers that they be treated as 
any other disadvantaged minority 
delegates to the fourth congress of the world of romany union 
discussed issues including standardizing their roma language 
discrimination memorializing gypsy victims of the naziholocaust 
and the potential dangers for gypsies posed by rising nationalism 
in eastern europe 
sessions were held at a steel mills country recreation center 
24 miles north of warsaw after somber speeches during the day the 
delegates gathered for singing and dancing in unbridled celebration 
of their heritage 
the conference was conducted in the gypsy roma language but 
with 20 major dialects worldwide delegates sometimes had difficulty 
making themselves understood to all participants 
gypsies or the romany as they prefer to be known are descended 
from nomadic tribes that left northwestern india sometime during 
the first millenium and made their first recorded appearance in 
western europe early in the 1400s 
their worldwide population is variously estimated at 5 million 
to more than 10 million 
the romany have been associated in popular lore with 
fortunetelling stealing and musicmaking and conference 
participants said the stereotypes had been forced upon them by 
gaje or nongypsies 
nobody takes us seriously said ian hancock a britishborn 
gypsy who teaches linguistics at the university of texas at austin 
we are one people who arrived in europe 800 years ago who have 
become fragmented by the hostility we encountered from europeans 
but now we must work toward becoming one people again he said 
the meeting elected poet rajko djuric of yugoslavia as president 
of the world romany union 
the union calls on all governments to treat gypsies as human 
beings djuric said we call for giving them the right to life 
and their own culture and language 
the first world meeting was held in 1971 in london but this was 
the first that delegates from the soviet union and albania were 
able to attend 
thanks to perestroika and democratization we are here said 
lev cerenkov of moscow who came with 15 other soviet citizens 
in the soviet union and most warsaw pact countries gypsies were 
forced by communist governments to give up their nomadic lifestyles 
after world war ii 
their horses were shot or taken away and the wheels removed from 
their painted wagons some still live in dilapidated barracks given 
to them at that time said stanislaw stankiewicz of poland 
europes gypsy population was devastated during the holocaust 
when 500000 to 1 million were put to death in gas chambers 
the genocide was only the culmination of the persecution for the 
gypsies hancock said many countries banned gypsies and some 
permitted them to be used as slaves or hunted 
the romantic interpretation of the wandering gypsy is not 
romantic at all hancock said it is really life on the run 
today gypsies suffer from lower education levels income and 
life expectancy than their nongypsy neighbors and often have 
trouble obtaining basic services or recognition hancock said 
if gypsies steal it is often subsistence theft to feed 
their families when discrimination prevents them from obtaining 
honest work he said 
we are thirdclass citizens said rudko kawczinski a former 
member of the european parliament from hamburg west germany 
the political changes in eastern europe which the west sees 
as very positively is starting to look bad for gypsies there is a 
backlash of prejudice against minorities hancock said 
there were many signs at the meeting of gypsy pride however 
many delegates sported gypsy flag lapel pins which are blue and 
green with a spoked wheel in the center the wheel of fire is 
from indian mythology and represents the gypsies origins in india 
hancock said 
some delegates said the romany must become more involved in 
politics at home 
what is important is getting people to notice us on this globe 
and understanding out culture and traditions said stankiewicz 
of bialystok who recently founded polands first romalanguage 
newspaper 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

