<DOCNO> AP900412-0121 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
brazils congress gave a major 
victory to president fernando collor de mello by passing intact the 
heart of his draconian antiinflation plan economists said a 
severe recession is a certainty 
in a surprising vote late wednesday legislators passed by 
249204 a measure that froze for 18 months all bank deposits of 
more than 1200 and money market deposits of more than 600 
i am extremely satisfied with the result of the congressional 
session collor told reporters as he headed for a pizzeria in 
brasilia to celebrate 
collor decreed the measure as part of a series of reforms 
launched mar 16 the day after he took office he said it was 
central to his strategy of beating 4854 percent annual inflation 
economic minister zelia cardoso de mello was exultant after the 
vote and said the legislators action would ensure the success of 
the new brazil plan 
but economists agreed that collors plan will produce a brutal 
recession at least in the short term 
a recession is inevitable its duration will depend on the 
governments future conduct of economic policy but i would not be 
surprised to see a 20 percent drop in industrial production over 
the next three months said edmar bacha an economist 
bacha who supports the plan said an economic downturn was 
necessary to end chronic inflation 
signs of an impending recession are everywhere the automobile 
capital goods construction and machine tools industries are 
virtually paralyzed unions say almost 1 million workers have 
either been fired taken pay cuts or been put on collective 
holiday 
the government will have to create special credit lines for 
badly hit sectors to prevent the recession from getting out of of 
control said mario henrique simonsen a conservative economist 
who served as finance minister between 1974 and 1979 when brazil 
was run by a rightwing military regime 
simonsen said the depth of the recession would depend on the 
publics confidence in the plan 
the bank confiscation has shaken the shortterm confidence of 
investors and savers in the financial system how they react in the 
longer term will be crucial he said 
leftist economists were especially critical 
we are going to have a deep and long depression you cant 
solve economic problems with this sort of drastic solution said 
paul singer a leading economist with the socialist workers party 
he said the workers party favored collective bargaining of wages 
and prices between labor unions and business to bring down 
inflation without producing a recession 
i am afraid of very serious social convulsions this downturn 
will be far worse than the 1983 recession he said during that 
recession the economy fell by 3 percent resulting in widescale 
looting of supermarkets and an increase in urban violence 
the logic of the plan is to paralyze the economy for several 
months and then make the recession tolerable but the shock was so 
strong im not sure how long it will be before we reach the 
tolerable stage said rep cesar maia an economist and spokesman 
for the centerleft democratic labor party 
maia criticized the government for not increasing unemployment 
benefits and taking other measures to cushion the blow for those 
who are directly hit by the recession but he said if the 
government managed the plan well the economy could begin to grow 
again in about a year 
simonsen said the longterm success of the plan depends on what 
happens when the government begins returning the money in frozen 
bank accounts 
