<TEXT>
the veterans affairs department wants to 
reverse its shortage of registered nurses by pegging pay to local 
rates in private hospitals 
while the plan would apply only to registered nurses it would 
move the government in the direction of paying its employees at 
levels comparable to those of private industry a goal of unions 
that represent federal workers 
it could be the precedent that gets us going through the work 
force said janice lachance spokeswoman for the 700000member 
american federation of government employees 
draft legislation given to the senate this week also would add 
pay incentives for nurse managers and supervisors 
the veterans affairs department is the nations largest employer 
of registered nurses with 35000 of them at work in its hospitals 
clinics and nursing homes 
starting base pay for a registered nurse employed by the 
department is 18174 the american nurses association the average 
starting salary nationwide for a registered nurse is 25261 
the american federation of government employees had opposed 
cocalled locality pay in the past but it now favors the concept 
as long as such a system includes safeguards advocated by the 
union ms lachance said she did not know whether the departments 
bill included those safeguards 
the administration last month proposed a pay scale for federal 
employees that accounts for local pay but the federal employee 
unions object to a feature of the proposal that eliminates step 
increases in certain job categories and instead links pay to 
performance 
under the proposal made by veterans affairs secretary edward j 
derwinski the department would use pay data from private hospitals 
to establish community rates 
but the national scale for nurses employed by the department 
would serve as a floor under their pay and the community rates 
would go into effect only if they exceeded that level 
also limits on certain categories overtime for some nurses 
would be lifted and pay rates would be flexible for certain 
nursespecialists premium pay increases would be given to head 
nurses and incentive pay would be allowed for nurse managers and 
executives 
the department already has made some adjustments to move closer 
to local rates but the process has proven so slow that the 
government has not caught up with levels in the private health care 
industry 
the department was paying special rates at 130 of its 172 
medical centers at year ago derwinski said 
even with the special rates va has not been able to offer 
competitive salaries at certain geographic locations such as 
boston southern california and new york city derwinski said in a 
letter to lawmakers 
committees in both the house and senate have been working on pay 
legislation for nurses and a similar measure for physicians and 
dentists also is on the drawing board 
