<TEXT>
the parliaments apology thursday to jews and 
other peoples who suffered under the nazi occupation marks a 
dramatic break from four decades of denying a dark past 
in a concisely worded declaration the parliament unanimously 
declared null and void the communist version of east german 
history which trumpeted the virtues of socialism and refused 
responsibility for any tragedies inflicted in the past by germans 
on other nations 
we the first freely elected parliamentarians of the german 
democratic republic east germany acknowledge the responsibility 
of germans in the german democratic republic for its history and 
its future the declaration said 
the declaration was adopted by the parliament was chosen last 
month in east germanys first free elections after more than 40 
years of communist rule 
east germany like other former communist countries in eastern 
europe has tried to break away from the official communist 
histories that often emphasized ideology over historical accuracy 
the parliaments declaration turned first to the horrors of the 
nazi period and acknowledged that immeasurable suffering was 
inflicted on the peoples of the world by germans 
national and racial illusions led to genocide especially of 
jews from all european countries it said 
the declaration could help the process of reconciling east 
germanys historical view of the holocaust with that prevailing in 
west germany 
west germany was compelled after world war ii to confront its 
nazi past years ago it apologized for nazi atrocities and began 
paying reparations to jewish victims 
east germany long maintained its communist leaders were also 
victims of nazi repression and therefore the country bore no 
responsibility for the deaths of 6 million jews during world war ii 
in its declaration the parliament dramatically distanced itself 
from the policies of the communist government toppled from power in 
october 
the first freely elected parliament in the name of the 
citizens of this country admits joint responsibility for the 
humiliation expulsion and murder of jewish women men and 
children the declaration said we feel grief and shame and 
acknowledge this burden of german history 
it asked forgiveness for the bad treatment of jews who remained 
in the country after the war and for east germanys policy toward 
the state of israel 
the declaration pledged to do everything possible to cultivate 
jewish culture and said asylum should be granted in east germany 
for jews persecuted elsewhere in the world 
it also said east germany is prepared to make reparations to 
jewish victims and urged establishment of diplomatic relations with 
israel 
the declaration then turned to the soviet union and poland 
where millions of people died at the hands of the nazis 
we have not forgotten the terrible pain that the germans in 
the second world war inflicted on people in the soviet union 
we want to intensively continue the process of reonciliation 
between our two peoples the declaration said 
parliament said that the political changes in east germany would 
not have been possible without soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachevs reforms 
it also sought to reassure poland which has expressed concern 
about german unification 
the parliament reiterated the communist governments earlier 
commitments abandoning any territorial claims on former german 
lands ceded to poland after world war ii 
the declaration said polands western border along the oder and 
neisse rivers was inviolable and should be guaranteed by a treaty 
passed by the future parliament of a united germany 
the declaration then apologized to another neighbor 
czechoslovakia for east germanys participation in the 1968 
sovietled warsaw pact invasion that crushed the prague spring 
reform movement 
out of fear and a lack of courage we did not hinder this 
breach of international law the declaration said the first 
freely elected parliament in the german democratic republic asks 
the people of czechoslovakia to pardon this occurrence of 
injustice 
