<TEXT>
the estimated cost of the pentagons major 
weapons programs increased by 31 billion or 38 percent in the 
last quarter of 1989 because of inflation and a slight increase in 
planned missiles and ships 
the pentagon in its congressionally required report released 
thursday offered a snapshot as of dec 31 of expected overall 
costs for 95 major weapons systems if president bushs military 
budget is enacted 
however the overall estimate now 8438 billion may change 
given that congress or defense secretary dick cheney may limit 
production on or terminate some weapons systems including the c17 
cargo plane and the ddg51 guidedmissile destroyer 
the previous report released in september predicted the 
overall cost of the major systems would be 8066 billion upward 
revisions in expected inflation rates are largely responsible for 
the higher costs the pentagon said 
the difference in the two figures is 372 billion but 
comparisons on an appleswithapples basis give a difference of 31 
billion because the new estimate includes 62 billion for a navy 
program that was not in the september figure 
that program is the socalled fixed distributed system a 
classified ocean surveillance project 
one of the major increases was for the midgetman strategic 
nuclear missile now put at 73 billion an increase of 19 
billion or 35 percent over the previous estimate 
the pentagon said the jump was primarily the result of restoring 
costs expected all along but excluded last year because of the way 
bush and congress handled midgetman in the current defense budget 
the fiscal 1990 budget contains less than 250 million for the 
mobile singlewarhead landbased missile with those funds the 
midgetman program amounted to a research and development project 
this is a reinstatement of the costs said roy lietza a 
spokesman for the air force 
among the increased costs for the midgetman are 13 billion for 
the missile and its basing with a goal of initial operation in 
1997 458 million for six additional research and development 
missiles and 87 million for inflation 
the estimated cost of the multiplewarhead mx nuclear missile 
dropped 39 billion from 23 billion primarily because of a 
reduction in the number of planned missiles from 255 to 193 the 
drop was partially offset by inflation increase estimated at 236 
million 
the estimates consist of the annual costs of research and 
development purchase of the weapon itself and associated 
construction added together for the several years each weapon will 
be bought sometimes extending into the next century cost of 
operations such as fuel and crew wages are not included 
one program which cheney is currently reviewing the arleigh 
burkeclass destroyer or ddg51 increased 4 billion from a 
previous estimate of 28 billion 
the navy cited an increase in the number of ships from 33 to 38 
and revised inflation rates as the reasons for the 15 percent jump 
the other navy program the defense secretary may curtail the 
ssn21 seawolf attack submarine dropped in estimated cost from 
20 billion to 16 billion because of a decrease in the number of 
submarines from 12 to nine 
the estimated cost of the c17 cargo plane also under review 
increased 44 billion from a previous price of 374 billion the 
air force blamed the rise on inflation and schedule changes due to 
plans to stretch out the program 
slower production rates frequently raise total costs by reducing 
production efficiency 
one of the largest increases in army programs was in the medium 
tactical vehicles in which the estimated cost jumped from 86 
billion to 161 billion or 88 percent 
the army attributed the rise to an increase in the number of 
trucks from 79157 to 102322 an extension of the modernization 
program from 15 to 30 years schedule changes and inflation 
the estimated cost of the m1 tank which cheney has proposed 
canceling in the budget for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 
dropped 6 billion due to a decrease in the number of tanks 
</TEXT>
