federal investigators have filed a complaint 
charging that immigration and naturalization service officials 
unlawfully retaliated against undercover agents in houston for 
writing to their congressmen 
the complaint filed wednesday with the federal merit systems 
protection board said the retaliation came after the antismuggling 
agents told lawmakers their undercover identifies were compromised 
by a change of assignment 
the 18count complaint was filed by the us office of special 
counsel it sought disciplinary action against three officials of 
the houston district office of the immigration and naturalization 
service 
named in the complaint were district director ronald parra 
deputy district director michael mcmahon and carey murphy 
assistant district director for investigations it alleged that 
they engaged in prohibited personnel practices 
the agents complained about a switch from antismuggling duty to 
employerrelations work created by a 1986 immigration law not only 
were their undercover identities jeopardized they said but they 
were told to falsify time cards and record time spent on employer 
relations as antismuggling hours 
after writing to lawmakers the six agents and two supervisors 
received low performance appraisals or were pressured to take 
unwanted transfers according to a separate investigation by the 
general accounting office 
ins spokesman duke austin said the merit systems protection 
board is the appropriate forum for the complaints and would not 
comment further 
