<TEXT>
president bush was diagnosed thursday with 
an early glaucoma in his left eye but he said it had not 
affected his vision 
the glaucoma was found during the presidents routine physical 
at bethesda naval hospital and will be treated with prescription 
eye drops press secretary marlin fitzwater said in a statement 
otherwise the 65yearold bush is in excellent health said 
white house physician dr burton lee in a statement released by the 
press office he continues to keep extremely fit through vigorous 
physical activities 
i havent felt a thing felt it at all bush told reporters 
im taking drops now one in the morning and one at night but 
the vision is very good 
fitzwaters statement said that during the examination an 
early glaucoma of his left eye was detected but that extensive 
tests showed no visual impairment 
with early detection and continual treatment the president 
should not develop vision problems said dr mansour armaly 
chairman of ophthalmology at george washington university medical 
center who did not examine bush but is a specialist in glaucoma 
although bush is not suffering impairment of his vision 
glaucoma can lead to blindness if not treated the disease is 
characterized by increased pressure and hardening of the eyeball 
it has no cure but can be controlled with drugs laser surgery 
may be performed on patients who dont respond to drugs armaly and 
other doctors said 
it is quite a high probability he will have none armaly 
said when asked about the prospects for vision problems it is a 
disease that requires regular follow up to make sure the medication 
is effective 
for the glaucoma he will receive betagan eyedrops one drop 
every 12 hours and will continue this medication permanently 
fitzwater said 
bush has had a stye in his right eye for the past week which is 
nearly gone after treatments with soaks and antibiotics fitzwater 
said 
betagan the brandname for the drug levobunolol is a 
betablocker similar to those that treat arterial high blood 
pressure that lowers the ocular pressure said armaly 
there are different types of glaucoma but all cause pressure 
within the eye as result of obstruction to the micro passages that 
allow ordinary fluid to leave the eye at the normal rate into the 
blood vessels he said 
unless the glaucoma is transitory resulting from something such 
as a previous blow to the eye it is considered a lifetime 
condition he said 
dr m bruce shields of the duke university eye center in 
durham nc said once glaucoma is found in one eye it often 
appears in the other but treatment can also save the sight in the 
second eye 
the white house reference to early glaucoma apparently means 
the nerve was not damaged enough to affect bushs vision said 
shields who is chairman of the glaucoma committee of the national 
committee to prevent blindness 
glaucoma is not unusual in a person in his 60s shields said 
the nspb estimates more than 2 million americans ages 35 and 
over have glaucoma but that nearly half are not aware of it the 
society says the disease accounts for one out of every eight cases 
of blindness in the united states 
the vision is very good the vision things working well 
bush told reporters thursday joking about his habit of attaching 
the word thing to topics critics during his 1988 presidential 
said he lacked the vision thing 
during the four hours of tests and examinations doctors also 
found that bushs hips and neck showed mild degenerative 
osteoarthritis a condition revealed in past physicals 
the white house said he also underwent chest xrays which were 
normal an electrocardiogram and stress tests which were normal 
urinalysis showing no abnormality blood tests which were normal a 
dermatology exam showing no significant problem or change 
his allergy problems remain minimal and unchanged fitzwater 
said 
bush emerged from the examination wearing sunglasses because 
his eyes had been dilated and called to reporters that he felt 
like a spring colt 
he told reporters all is well on his return to the white 
house 
the presidents last physical was may 10 1989 and he was 
pronounced in good health 
the only problem cited during last years physical was a cyst on 
the third finger of bushs right hand the cyst was surgically 
removed last october and later was found to be benign 
</TEXT>
