<TEXT>
american jewish leaders welcomed the east german 
parliaments long overdue apology thursday for the holocaust 
and said the new government must include education in its effort to 
make amends 
apology must be accompanied with deeds said benjamin meed 
president of the 65000member american gatheringfederation of 
jewish holocaust survivors they must educate future generations 
to know what their fathers did and how they will prevent it from 
happening again 
it is 45 years overdue but apology is always good added 
meed a 70yearold survivor of the warsaw ghetto 
by making the apology east germanys first freely elected 
legislature ended four decades of denials by its former communist 
leaders that the country played any role in the deaths of 6 million 
jews during world war ii 
nobody can bring back the dead but its a long overdue 
statement said rabbi a james rudin director of interreligious 
affairs of the 50000member american jewish committee 
east germanys legislature also promised to make reparations to 
israel and to seek diplomatic ties with that country israel has 
long demanded reparations and an east german apology for nazi 
crimes as a condition for diplomatic relations 
before you can have normalization there had to be admission 
of guilt remorse said rabbi arthur schneier a holocaust survivor 
and president of the interreligious appeal of conscience foundation 
this is a first step in a normalization process and it has to 
be advanced by education and reeducation said schneier all 
these years east germans were conditioned to the fact that we had 
nothing to do with it it is a great challenge to educate the 
public and particularly the younger generation as to the tragedy of 
the holocaust so that another tragedy of this kind would be 
averted 
