patients have the right to refuse lifesustaining 
medical treatment but active euthanasia is wrong said a report 
released thursday nearly a year after a gunwielding father 
disconnected his comatose babys life support 
the time has come to return control over the dying process to 
patients and their families said the report 
the report was written by a task force formed by cook county 
states attorney cecil partee after the april 26 incident at 
rushpresbyterianst lukes medical center 
rudy linares holding hospital workers at bay with a gun turned 
off his 15monthold sons respirator and cradled the baby in his 
arms until he died 
officials at the hospital had refused family requests to halt 
life support 
a grand jury refused to charge linares with murder he pleaded 
guilty to a misdemeanor charge of unlawful possession of a weapon 
and was ordered to seek psychological counseling 
the report should have been done long before so this wouldnt 
have occurred linares said in a telephone interview thursday 
adding that he had no regrets over his actions 
illinois law allows people to decline life support through 
living wills or by assigning power of attorney to a third party 
model legislation drafted by the task force would allow people to 
refuse life support without taking such actions 
partee wrote legislation similar to the model bill it was 
introduced last week in the illinois senate 
the task force said a person should be judged capable of making 
the decision to end life support before medical officials take such 
action the task force said surrogates could make the decision for 
those judged not capable and that parents could decide for children 
a judicial ruling would be needed only in cases of a dispute 
the task force said noting that doctors and surrogates should be 
immune from criminal prosecution for decisions made in good faith 
the task force said its report was in no way intended to 
endorse the practice of active euthanasia or mercy killing 
at the time the task force was formed there were no state court 
rulings on the issue earlier this year the illinois supreme court 
ruled that life support could be withheld from terminally ill 
patients when they are diagnosed as irreversibly comatose and when 
a doctors diagnosis was confirmed by two other physicians 
the task forces work was praised by fenella rouse director of 
the new yorkbased concern for dying and the society for the right 
to die 
