news hijuelos said in a telephone interview from ulster county 
the news couldnt have been better mambo kings had won the 
pulitzer prize for fiction 
this is so unexpected said hijuelos the son of cuban 
immigrants and a resident of manhattan ive just been in england 
and i was spending the week here to chill out i didnt even know 
when they were going to announce this thing my mother will be 
happy 
mambo kings cesar and nestor castillo would have understood 
theyre the cuban brothers who immigrated to the united states and 
through their friendship with desi arnaz wound up on stage at the 
tropicana and in the living room of ricky and lucy ricardo in 
hijuelos own special episode of i love lucy 
it really started out as a novel about a superintendent who 
had a past life hijuelos said of his second novel his past 
life was about music and then the music took over it ties into my 
cuban roots and also into my interest in the culture in general 
you always get that second novelitis said hijuelos whose 
first novel our house in the last world was published in 
1985 so what happened was simply amazing to me 
hijuelos born in new york in 1951 originally wanted to be a 
rock n roll star but was turned off by the drug scene he nearly 
quit writing as well attending a conference in 1978 and finding it 
the most sexist hierarchal opinionated prejudical place ive 
ever been on earth 
fortunately hijuelos became friendly with author donald 
barthelme who encouraged the young writer to develop his own style 
and even offered tips on the secrets of success 
he said if youre good you eventually get recognized sooner 
or later hijuelos said of barthelme who died of cancer last 
year 
i figured i had 20 years to go to get these kinds of breaks 
he always spoke about awards as an important kind of thing i think 
its a way for writers investing into their future it helps 
people it helps writers and the readers they identify with 
hijuelos gets letters from people all over the country telling 
him they can relate to the experiences of the castillo brothers and 
expressing curiosity about the world he evokes 
the united states is a country of immigrants and i think 
people who are still in touch with feelings of displacement could 
tap into the characters in the novel he said 
i guess on another level people are tired of the a fits into 
b kind of formulaic novels i wanted to do something different i 
tried to structure the book musically i also hope it means that 
people feel differently about the kind of people i wrote about 
hijuelos working on a new novel tentatively titled 14 
sisters says winning the pulitzer is just the tip of the 
iceberg for him and so many others ready to tell their stories 
i think culturally the establishment has in homegrown 
latin writers a potential source of great literature most writing 
from minorities is on small presses and university presses 
maybe this will encourage publishers to move over a little bit 
</TEXT>
