a senior legislator said thursday that up to 70 
percent of the soviet state economy could be turned over to private 
hands in radical economic reforms likely to begin next year 
but pavel bunich deputy chairman of a supreme soviet committee 
on economic reform was unsure whether the government would be bold 
enough to press that hard for such largescale reforms 
if we want to take small steps we will get nowhere but to a 
general collapse bunich told a news conference 
president mikhail s gorbachev said earlier this week that he 
will meet saturday with his presidential council and the council of 
the federation to hear the governments proposals for radical 
economic changes 
he said that reforms previously scheduled to take effect in 
199293 in a plan presented by premier nikolai i ryzhkov four 
months ago should be moved up to this year and next 
bunich predicted that opponents of such radical reform a 
fundamental change in the statebased soviet economy will 
complain loudly at the supreme soviet but he said the reforms are 
likely to be approved permitting them to go into effect in 1991 
if we are talking about denationalization about 70 percent 
of the public sector will cease to exist bunich said there 
are many people who want to buy shops workshops and small 
enterprises 
such a shift would mean not only putting business in private 
hands but freeing up prices of goods produced and sold by the 
private sector bunich said 
it also would cut drastically into the work of government 
ministries and the agencies that handle economic planning pricing 
and supply he said 
bunich told reporters that he did not favor a polishstyle 
shock therapy approach to economic reform including a sudden 
freeing of prices devaluation of the currency and rapid increases 
in unemployment 
public opposition and danger of social upheavals is the main 
danger we are facing here he said 
instead he said economists are looking at an approach closer to 
yugoslavias based on wage controls 
that approach has cut the rate of inflation drastically in 
yugoslavia this year he said prices are beginning to stabilize 
in yugoslavia we are studying the yugoslav option he said 
asked whether ryzhkovs government agrees on the need to return 
the majority of the economy to private hands bunich said 
government ministers have some exact formulas but some of them 
are so porous that its just impossible to tell whether the 
government agrees or not 
after ryzhkovs government makes its proposals to gorbachev he 
is likely to address the supreme soviet legislature at the end of 
the month with a final blueprint of economic reform that will 
require new laws and directives 
