<TEXT>
state environmental officials on 
thursday held a federal agency and a grain elevator operator 
equally responsible for cleaning up 12755 bushels of corn heavily 
tainted by a natural cancercausing toxin 
the order from the iowa division of environmental protection 
gave the farmers home administration and the pruess elevator co of 
lowden which purchased the corn until next friday to remove it 
but a lawyer representing the fmha which sold the corn from a 
foreclosed farm at chouteau okla and knew it was tainted 
insisted the agency has no responsibility the owner of the 
elevator harlan pruess continued to decline to comment thursday 
the grain is believed to have the highest concentration of 
aflatoxin ever found in this country as much as 1600 times the 
maximum allowable limit for human consumption said dale cochran 
iowas secretary of agriculture regional officials of the us 
food and drug administration in kansas city mo also said the 
aflatoxin level is the highest theyve ever come across 
aflatoxins are cancercausing and toxic substances produced by 
certain soil fuingi 
the food and drug administration says aflatoxin concentrations 
above 20 parts per billion are unsuitable for human consumption and 
concentrations above 300 parts per billion are unsuitable for 
animal feed 
fda tests of the corn found concentrations as high as 32300 
parts per billion in one sample in its bill of sale the fmha 
disclosed that the corn contained aflatoxin concentrations greater 
than 5000 parts per billion and assigned any liability to the 
purchaser 
it shouldnt be fed to anything said gary osweiler a 
veterinary toxicologist at iowa state university 
an animal fed such tainted corn probably would become ill 
within a day or so youd probably kill animals he said 
an fmha lawyer declined to say why the agency had sold the 
grain except to say that the sale had not been banned by federal 
or state authorities 
speedy action by the iowa department of agriculture prevented 
the corn from being fed to animals or winding up in milk or meat 
products state and federal officials said 
oklahoma officials notified counterparts in iowa once tests 
disclosed the aflatoxin concentrations in the early march shipment 
and iowa inspectors were on hand to quarantine the corn when it 
arrived 
dust from the tainted corn could be a health risk but 
fortunately the corn is covered with a protective crust in part 
because of the high moisture content that also enabled the fungi to 
grow said allan stokes director of the environmental protection 
division within iowas department of natural resources 
its kind of like a scab its best not to pick on it till you 
know what to do stokes said 
the corn is quarantined piled on a concrete slab surrounded by 
concrete retaining walls next to the elevator in a sparsely 
settled area three miles outside lowden in eastern iowa stokes 
said 
iowa environmental authorities set a deadline of april 20 for 
implementing an acceptable plan to get the corn out of the state 
or remove the threat from the corn stokes said 
stokes estimated the cleanup cost at around 100000 while 
cochran has placed it as high as 15 million the grain was sold 
for 9566 
robert bird an attorney in the us department of agricultures 
office of general counsel in stillwater okla represents the fmha 
i dont see how the state of iowa could hold the fmha 
coresponsible because the fmha has no ownership interest bird 
said in a telephone interview 
he said the fda and the oklahoma department of agriculture both 
knew in advance of the intended sale and if either had told the 
fmha to destroy the corn the fmha would do it 
but he said aside from informing the fmha of the maximum 
allowable limits of aflatoxin in animal feed or for human 
consumption there was no directive banning the sale 
