<TEXT>
james galway loves to travel with his 
audiences on musical adventures that make different tunes dance 
from his flute 
he plays beethoven with a smile and irish ballads with the 
chieftains last year he toured with 30 children and the baltimore 
symphony as the pied piper of hamelin in a musical fantasy 
written especially for him by composer john corigliano 
now hes coming out with a new lp the enchanted forest 
galway teamed up with a roomful of synthesizers to make the album 
and then topped it off with an mtv video 
but galway doesnt know how to describe the new work because he 
dislikes labels 
so dont call it new wave he said just call it a unique 
type of which there is no other like it 
galway loves music and his temper can flare up at anyone or 
anything that tries to complicate it even the contracts he must 
sign for all of his ventures must be straightforward we have a 
rule in our office if we cant read it we dont sign it he 
says 
last year he turned 50 and classical magazine calls this period 
the golden days of galway as the flutist allows himself to pick 
and choose his schedule 
i can think of a lot of things i want to do and what i cant 
think of somebody else does he says with a laugh i sure 
dont need the money so i do the ones i want to do 
he makes his opera debut april 16 in a new production of 
rossinis the thieving magpie the next evening he begins a 
tour in california that ends may 9 in new york with a stop at 
the tonight show starring johnny carson 
he has a performance schedule that goes from here to there and 
back interjects his wife jeanne who travels with him she 
performs with him in chamber groups and will play the part of the 
magpie in the second and final philadelphia performance on april 20 
the idea to play the title role in rossinis the thieving 
magpie was not galways 
i had never thought of it before and no one else did it 
before so i decided to do it galway says 
the opera had its american debut in 1827 in philadelphia but no 
flutist has ever been cast as the magpie 
during rehearsals in philadelphia galways impish side surfaced 
from time to time at one point he put a boom box on his 
shoulder and said james galway and the 20 best hits from the 
street hows that for my new album 
underneath the wit the blunt charm and the bantering nature 
that has endeared him to audiences galway is very serious about 
his craft and is devoted to practice sessions hes also fiercely 
independent about his way whatever way that may be at the moment 
of playing 
i wouldnt play in an orchestra now he says i wouldnt 
want to narrow my music down 
however galway did branch into serious acting once 
i needed money while i was between guildhall school in 
london and the paris conservatory so i took a year off and did 
shakespeare at stratfordonavon he said 
but he said he was never serious about a switch ive always 
thought of music nothing else 
it was the combination of acting and music complete with a 
costume and intricate staging while playing his magic flute that 
appealed to galway in doing the opera 
rossini originally wrote the work using an actor as the magpie 
who stole the silver spoon and caused a young servant girl to be 
sentenced to death the opera company of philadelphia decided in 
the first american production of the work in this century to create 
a special role for someone such as galway 
the rolling notes that galway plays as he flits about the stage 
were borrowed from passages rossini wrote for the violin and flute 
as parts of the orchestra 
for his motions on stage galway draws on his own observations 
of the bird an outgrowth of his interest in the animal kingdom 
he talked about the latest television program he had enjoyed on 
animals in the wild then with a burst of galway directness denied 
that his performance was to be a statement on anything but music 
i didnt study birds for years to do this i studied music 
he says it just so happens that i would know a dead magpie in 
the road if i saw one 
