<DOCNO> AP900412-0195 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the use of dna identification to link suspects 
to crimes is being successfully challenged by defense attorneys in 
a small but growing number of cases 
at issue are the reliability of the tests and the way they are 
conducted 
in the last year i am aware of at least seven or eight cases 
where after the defense got an expert involved the prosecution has 
withdrawn the evidence says lawyer peter neufeld who 
successfully challenged dna test results in a new york city murder 
case last summer 
the judge in the case cited problems with the laboratory 
analysis 
since it was first introduced in a us criminal court in 1987 
dna testing has been presented in 200 cases in at least 36 states 
the fbi opened its own dna lab in late 1988 to test samples for 
state and local police departments since then bureau experts have 
presented evidence that has helped convict 44 people 
with everything we have seen so far we are gaining confidence 
in the dna identifications utility in serving the criminal justice 
community said john hicks head of the fbis laboratory division 
the tests compare genetic material extracted from tissue or body 
fluids found at crime scenes with dna from a suspects blood 
while law enforcement authorities hail dna identification 
defense lawyers have won several victories by exposing what courts 
found to be flaws in testing procedures 
among them 
the minnesota supreme court refused in november to admit dna 
test results in a murder case saying the laboratory of cellmark 
diagnostics in germantown md did not meet standards for 
scientific reliability 
in december prosecutors in maine were forced to withdraw dna 
evidence in a sexual assault case and drop charges 
defense experts testified there were flaws in procedures used by 
lifecodes corp of valhalla ny to match dna in the defendants 
blood with that extracted from a semen sample taken at the crime 
scene 
on march 8 a judge presiding over an oregon rape case refused 
to admit dna test results from the fbi lab ruling there was too 
much scientific controversy over the tests reliability and too 
much danger of confusing jurors with technical details 
spokesmen at the two commercial dna laboratories defended their 
procedures as did hicks 
hicks said computer imaging at the fbi lab ensures that a match 
is properly read by the tester in addition two examiners must 
find that the dna patterns match before positive results are 
declared he said 
michael baird director of forensic testing at lifecodes said 
the court decisions have not discredited the technique or the 
procedures track record 
we are talking about whether the approach itself is correct as 
opposed to whats being done in a particular case baird said 
there have been situations where portions of the evidence were 
not ruled admissible but the technology itself has been 
admissible 
the issue is not so much should it be accepted as evidence but 
how and under what circumstances said janlori goldman a staff 
attorney for the american civil liberties unions privacy project 
dna testing isnt exclusively a weapon for prosecutors 
of more than 500 tests completed by the fbi 36 percent excluded 
the suspect in question hicks said 
public defenders in washington commissioned dna tests that 
recently exonerated a man whose rape conviction was overturned 
because his dna did not match that taken from a semen stain found 
on the womans clothing 
thousands of other tests performed by cellmark and lifecodes 
have exonerated defendants or encouraged them to plead guilty said 
mark storolow a spokesman for cellmark 
as a form of evidence it must be very very powerful because 
it results in a lot of plea bargaining he said 
rape cases are the most common application of dna testing in 
criminal investigations because hospitals routinely take semen 
samples from victims 
the test can also be useful in solving murders enabling police 
to determine for example that blood on a suspects clothing was 
from the victim it also is used for paternity tests 
when it goes to the identity of the person thats when its 
particularly relevant said jay b stephens the us attorney in 
washington 
to check for a match scientists use enzymes to cut dna 
strands into small pieces and place them on laboratory gelatin the 
fragments move along the gelatin and form patterns similar to the 
pricecode bars on supermarket merchandise 
each person except for identical twins has a singular genetic 
makeup so the pattern should be unique 
based on the size of the test sample and data taken from dna 
tests drawn from samplings of the population scientists calculate 
the odds against a pattern being repeated 
neufeld and other lawyers argue that laboratories use 
lessthanobjective criteria for deciding that two dna patterns 
match 
in the maine case expert witnesses questioned the procedures 
lifecodes used to adjust for a phenomenon called bandshifting 
in which the fragments do not move evenly along the gelatin 
thomas caskey a medical professor who is starting a dna lab at 
baylor university in houston dismisses those who question the 
reliability of tests 
it is extremely easy to determine whether one has a match 
between the suspect and the forensic specimen he said 
but neufeld argues that like other scientific evidence dna 
should be subject to rigorous court scrutiny particularly if its 
used to determine if a person is going to prison 
</TEXT>
