<TEXT>
a study of more than 12800 men bolsters research 
arguing that quitting smoking and eating lowfat foods can help 
lower the risk of heart disease 
the study published in the april 6 journal of the american 
medical association found that men at high risk for heart disease 
who were given dietary advice and other special treatment had a 24 
percent lower death rate from heart attacks than those who received 
ordinary care 
the death rate from heart disease was 106 percent lower and the 
overall death rate was 77 percent lower in the first group 
researchers found 
treatment consisted of advice to lower cholesterol levels 
counseling on quitting smoking and improved drug therapy to control 
high blood pressure 
about half the 12860 men studied at 22 clinics nationwide 
received the special treatment several times a year while the 
other half were examined annually and received additional treatment 
only if needed 
the study of men aged 35 to 57 began in late 1973 and ended in 
1982 the results reported in jama occurred between 1982 and a 
december 1985 followup review said marcus o kjelsberg a 
statistician at the university of minnesotas school of public 
health where the data was analyzed 
initial examinations in 1982 showed no significant differences 
between the groups which surprised researchers and prompted the 
followup kjelsberg said in a telephone interview 
the ultimate results were not surprising given the multitude of 
data showing a link between diet smoking and heart disease said 
jeremiah stamler a cardiovascular epidemiologist at northwestern 
university and a principal investigator in the study 
researchers expected to see the results earlier at the end of 
the study but they failed to anticipate several factors that may 
account for the delay stamler said 
one reason may have been that all the volunteers were relatively 
healthy despite facing a higher than normal risk for heart disease 
because they smoked had high blood pressure or high cholesterol 
levels or a combination of the three stamler said 
another reason for the delayed results may have been a change in 
drug treatment for high blood pressure that occurred toward the end 
of the study the later treatment was considered more effective 
kjelsberg said 
researchers did not determine how many of the men who had 
received special treatment continued to seek it after the study 
ended he said but they asssumed that many stuck to their 
healthier lifestyles 
the study was funded by the national heart lung and blood 
institute in bethesda md 
</TEXT>
