<TEXT>
an 11month declining trend in japans trade 
surplus halted in march but economists said it was because the 
months imports were being compared with an unusually large amount 
of imports in march 1989 
the finance ministry on thursday reported a surplus of 709 
billion in march up from 661 billion in march a year earlier in 
each of the 11 previous months the surplus had been smaller than 
the ones the prior year 
in february the surplus had fallen to 501 billion from 723 
billion in february 1989 
for japans fiscal year which ended march 31 the surplus 
measured when goods pass through customs fell to 597 billion 
from 789 billion the prior year the ministry reported 
in trade with the united states which has been pressing japan 
in a series of talks to narrow the imbalance the march surplus 
contracted to 377 billion from 401 billion in march 1989 
for the fiscal year japans sales to the united states exceeded 
us sales here by 428 billion down 127 percent from the 49 
billion surplus the year before 
on a global basis japans exports in march fell 18 percent 
from the previous year to 26 billion but imports declined 48 
percent to 189 billion 
in march 1989 imports had climbed nearly 30 percent from the 
previous year said toshiaki kakimoto chief economist with 
sumitomo bank there was a surge of buying before japan imposed a 
new 3 percent sales tax last april 1 he said 
meanwhile the us dollars recent increase against the yen 
makes japans exports measured in dollars appear bigger 
in march the finance ministry used exchange rates of about 148 
yen to one dollar to calculate exports and imports up from about 
128 yen a year earlier 
theres no big change in the downward trend of the japanese 
surplus said jan vandenberg an economist with merrill lynch in 
tokyo 
but she said that in coming months a combination of weaker 
demand in japan stronger demand abroad and the weak yen will cause 
japans trade surplus to begin expanding again 
kakimoto predicted a surplus of about 60 billion in the current 
fiscal year compared with 597 billion in fiscal 1989 
</TEXT>
