<TEXT>
energy futures prices mostly were higher in 
seesaw trading today after breaking a weeklong slump with some 
modest gains in the previous session 
prices had declined early in the session but recovered the days 
lost ground and more by midday 
the erratic performance came in the wake of official 
confirmation that opec oil ministers were considering calling an 
emergency meeting to deal with conditions that have seen crude oil 
futures prices fall 25 percent since january 
wednesdays gains came in one of the wildest sessions of the 
year as prices rocketed higher in the afternoon on speculation 
that opec nations were considering calling an emergency meeting 
prices had fallen sharply to start wednesdays session in what 
analysts said reflected concerns about the huge supply of crude and 
weak demand 
in london today opecs acting president sadek boussena said 
opec oil ministers are considering various options including 
calling an emergency meeting to try and stop the recent slide in 
world oil prices 
on the new york mercantile exchange at midday the may contract 
for west texas intermediate the benchmark grade of us crude oil 
was up 9 cents at 1815 a barrel on the new york mercantile 
exchange it had been down 44 cents at midmorning after rising 38 
cents on wednesday 
among refined products traded on the merc the contract for may 
delivery of unleaded gasoline was off 008 cent at 5950 cents a 
gallon after rising 115 cents on wednesday 
may home heating oil was up 047 cent to 5410 cents a gallon in 
early trading after rising 123 cents on wednesday 
meanwhile natural gas for june delivery was trading at 1597 
per million british thermal units down from 1605 on wednesday 
analysts said the early price declines on wednesday reflected 
the american petroleum institutes report released after the 
market closed tuesday that us crude oil inventories rose by a 
largerthanexpected 81 million barrels last week 
but prices rebounded sharply later in the session after rumors 
circulated that opec nations were consulting by telephone and 
considering calling an emergency meeting about the decline 
spokesmen for the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
at the groups headquarters in vienna said no meeting had been 
planned 
analysts say opec has been producing more crude oil than the 
market can absorb in recent weeks causing prices to decline since 
late january 
it has been estimated that the opec nations have been producing 
between 235 million and 241 million barrels a day of crude oil 
topping its selfimposed cap of 221 million barrels 
the only thing that can turn this market around would be 
opec said james r fiedler a vice president at edampf man 
international futures inc 
crude oil prices have plunged 25 percent since the nearmonth 
contract for west texas intermediate reached 2420 a barrel on 
jan 22 the decline had accelerated in recent days with the may 
crude oil contract losing 147 a barrel in this weeks first two 
sessions alone sinking to the lowest level for a nearmonth 
contract since february 1989 
despite the big decline in crude futures motorists havent seen 
lower prices at the pump 
the national average price for a gallon of gasoline was 11331 
a gallon on april 6 according to the latest lundberg survey of 
13000 gasoline stations nationwide that compared with an average 
11306 on jan 19 
analysts say there often is a lag of a month to 45 days for 
refined products to reflect movements in futures prices in 
addition they say gasoline prices normally rise as the spring 
driving season approaches and refiners this year are incurring 
extra costs in meeting tougher antismog regulations for their 
products 
demand for crude oil normally falls off in the early spring and 
refineries often take the opportunity to close their plants for 
maintenance 
but this spring inventories already were high because of an 
unusually mild winter in europe and the united states according to 
bob baker who tracks the oil markets for prudentialbache 
securities inc 
demand also appears to be weaker than a year ago peter beutel 
assistant director of the energy group at elders futures inc 
estimated demand for gasoline is down 12 percent from a year ago 
while demand for heating oil fell 85 percent 
part of the decline beutel said may stem from a general 
weakening in economic activity 
