<TEXT>
intel corp said thursday its 
firstquarter profit jumped 48 percent due in part to increased 
demand for the companys 32bit computer microprocessors 
profit for the quarter ended march 31 totaled 144 million or 
73 cents a share compared with 97 million or 52 cents a share 
in the same period a year ago 
revenue for the quarter totaled 894 million up 25 percent from 
713 million in the same quarter last year 
the transition to 32bit computer architectures has picked 
up momentum in the past six months said andrew s grove 
president and chief executive officer of the santa clarabased 
company 
intels new 386 and 486 microprocessors process information 32 
bits at a time rather than 16 bits under their original design a 
bit is the smallest piece of information used by a computer the 
increase expands microprocessor power capabilities and speed said 
intel spokeswoman karen nalley 
grove predicted continued market demand and growth for intel 
products in the current quarter 
intel has announced plans to upgrade or expand manufacturing 
capacity at several of its plants with capital expenditures for 
the year estimated at 600 million 
in december the company announced it was phasing out its last 
chip plant in silicon valley and moving production operations to 
other locations such as arizona oregon and new mexico where there 
is more affordable housing 
intel also said last year it is spending 400 million to build a 
plant near dublin ireland 
the company in january announced a joint venture with nmb 
semiconductor ltd of japan to sell nmbs dynamic randomaccess 
memory or dram chips worldwide on an exclusive basis 
intel used to manufacture drams a vital ingredient in many 
electronic products but quit in 1985 when japanese companies 
started making them in large quantities and selling them at low 
prices 
