<DOCNO> AP900412-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the decline of hostile takeovers may have 
restored a measure of calm to the boardrooms of us corporations 
but that doesnt mean directors and managers are enjoying peace and 
quiet 
their biggest shareholders institutional investors such as 
publicemployee pension funds that once endorsed nearly everything 
corporate executives said or did have become increasingly vocal 
and more demanding 
they are increasingly sponsoring resolutions at annual meetings 
for example on subjects ranging from shareholder proxyvoting 
rights to policies on the environment and south africa much to the 
chagrin of top executives some big investors have muscled their 
way into corporate decisionmaking 
were seeing companies voluntarily agreeing to institute 
confidentiality in proxy votesand occidental petroleum agreed 
to meet with institutional investors on an informal basis gray 
davis californias comptroller and a trustee of the states public 
employee pension funds said in citing examples of the 
institutions evolving power 
perhaps the biggest coup scored by institutional investors came 
last month at lockheed corps annual meeting when the big 
stockholders forced management to make some substantial concessions 
or risk losing their support in a proxy vote instigated by 
dissident investor harold simmons 
lockheed chairman daniel tellep met with 70 institutions in his 
defense against simmons campaign to unseat his companys board 
among the concessions tellep made was an agreement to name up to 
three lockheed directors to represent institutional shareholders 
he convinced me that he has finally got religion davis said 
of tellep he said the last three months of his life have been 
the most educational of his career 
davis said the institutions victory with lockheed will open 
doors at other corporations that sell stock to the public 
management is increasingly affording institutional investors an 
opportunity to make constructive suggestions he said 
institutional investors are trying to do what any investor wants 
to do make a profit the price of the stock they hold must be at 
or above a certain level or the value of assets needed to fund 
thousands of pensions will fall 
for example if a pension fund held 1 million shares of a 
companys stock and the stock fell 10 million over the course of a 
year the funds assets would be worth 10 million less than a year 
earlier that means theres less money to fund retirees pensions 
lockheeds stock reached a high of 5475 a share during the 
last 12 months but fell to 3662 by march 29 the day of the 
companys annual meeting for california public employees 
retirement system one of the funds of which davis is a trustee 
the 18ashare drop meant a decline of more than 9 million in its 
assets 
the stocks of other defense contractors also have fallen 
recently but the institutions and other shareholders including 
simmons have been dissatisfied with the companys management and 
linked its policies directly to the decline in lockheeds stock 
price 
if theyre so unhappy why dont they just sell their stock 
they cant at least not in one fell swoop with their massive 
holdings institutions cant unload an underperforming stock 
without affecting the rest of the market 
recently the california new york city and massachusetts 
pension funds jointly sought assurances from exxon corp that the 
oil giant would protect its earnings and therefore its stock 
price by taking steps to prevent another disaster like last 
years exxon valdez spill the funds said they approached the 
company because they couldnt just dump their combined holdings of 
14 million exxon shares 
todd lang a partner with the law firm weil gotshal amp manges 
said institutions are more active because they are forced to hold 
onto their shares 
institutional investors have a responsibility to their 
beneficiaries to seek changes or to vote independentlyso they 
develop voting positions on everything lang said 
many big companies have resisted institutions attempts to take 
a larger role in corporate governance when the california public 
employees fund and the new york state and local retirement system 
recently asked general motors corp for updates on the search for a 
successor to retiring chairman roger smith for example they were 
told to butt out 
corporate governance which includes the selection of 
officers is the boards responsibility gm said in a statement 
last year exxon named an environmentalist to its board in 
response to a request by new york citys employee pension fund but 
the request came less than two months after the exxon valdez 
accident the oil company fighting criticism about its 
environmental record was in no position to refuse 
despite the institutions recent gains some pension fund 
executives say there is still much work to be done 
roland m machold director of new jerseys investment division 
sees institutional holders as largely powerless although they hold 
40 percent to 50 percent of all outstanding stock 
he attributed much of the successes institutional holders had 
with lockheed to the threat generated by simmons one of the few 
takeover strategists who has remained relatively active in recent 
months 
certainly we have made our presence known but companies have 
tried to close the door on shareholder activity he said 
nonetheless investor relations consultants are warning 
management that institutional investors will be rocking the boat 
harder and told them this will be increasingly evident at annual 
meetings dale gerboth a partner at the accounting and consulting 
firm ernst amp young told companies recently institutional 
investors are acting more like owners 
machold and davis are two of three cochairmen of the council of 
institutional investors an association of employee benefit plans 
state and local agencies that oversee such plans and 
notforprofit foundations and endowments the council has become 
an advocate for shareholder rights in the belief that more powerful 
investors can help effect changes that will benefit all 
stockholders 
the council backs a set of proposals known as the shareholders 
bill of rights which among other things includes the principle of 
oneshare onevote and calls for shareholders to have a voice in 
matters that would have significant financial impact on a company 
institutional investors are also opposing some classic takeover 
defenses including antitakeover laws and poison pill plans 
which could limit their ability to receive a higher price for their 
shares in a buyout 
some have actively pressured companies to rescind corporate 
policies that award multimillion dollar golden parachute 
severance packages to executives if theyre dismissed 
californias funds have also been active on their own 
submitting to the securities and exchange commission proposed 
revisions on proxy solicitation rules 
we believe shareholders and employees should be afforded the 
opportunity to make constructive suggestions to management the 
proxy rules as presently constituted dont really afford 
shareholders that opportunity davis said 
our goal is a more level playing field he said under 
current law management has the upper hand 
</TEXT>
