<TEXT>
most of the junk bonds that financed the 
megatakeover of rjr nabisco inc are due in 2007 but recent 
gyrations in prices of the volatile bonds indicate how speculators 
are betting on the companys chances of paying them off 
earlier this week some highyield nabisco issues rose as much as 
4 points or about 45 per 1000 in face value before easing 
thursday as investors cashed in gains 
although nabisco is considered one of the less risky issues in 
the market for highyield debt its bonds have been volatile for 
months 
traders recently have focused on rumors that kohlberg kravis 
roberts amp co which bought nabisco last year for a record 2453 
billion might be buying up an issue of bonds to avoid having to 
pay sharply higher interest on them next year 
but others say the bond price jump reflects anticipation of a 
favorable firstquarter earnings report for the tobacco and 
consumer products giant 
nabsicos first quarter earnings due out later this month are 
expected to show a marked improvement over the previous quarter 
when the company lost 144 million nabisco lost 115 billion for 
all of 1989 but had positive cash flow of 647 million after all 
interest payments were made 
if the market gets some feeling that the company is doing a 
great job then the bonds will go up and react more like stocks 
to the news said jack maxwell an analyst at wheat first 
securities in richmond va 
both nabisco and kkr have a keen interest in seeing the bonds 
trade at high prices 
although the bulk of bonds about 45 billion worth dont 
mature until 2007 their interest rate must be reset in april 
1991 or adjusted to restore the bond price to face value 
bond prices move inversely to their interest rates so the lower 
the price of the rjr nabisco bonds the higher the interest rate 
the company must offer at the reset some market watchers 
speculate for example that the rate on rjrs 1371 percent 
convertible bonds due in 2007 might have to be reset at 20 percent 
or more 
rumors circulating in the marketplace indicate kkr might be in 
the process of buying back 2 billion of bonds due in 2009 that are 
convertible to stock 
analysts say such a move not only would increase kkrs stake in 
nabisco but also likely would help boost the value of other 
outstanding nabisco junk bonds helping cut the potential reset 
interest rate 
spokespeople for both kkr and nabisco had no comment thursday on 
the rumors 
its not the first time kkr has been rumored to be buying the 
bonds said joan greenberg senior vice president at dean witter 
reynolds inc but we saw greater price movement this time 
she said 
despite the recent upturn in prices some believe it hasnt been 
enough to allay nabiscos and kkrs concerns 
when you face a reset the main problem is the interest 
expense might be too much for a company to bear said robert 
waill a vice president at the stamford co a manhattanbased 
investment management firm you can be assured that the kkr 
people are thinking about his problem 
but wheat firsts maxwell believes the time ahead of the reset 
date will help nabisco if positive fundamental data emerges on the 
company and the bond prices rise the less you have to worry 
about them and the more people there will be buying them he 
said 
maxwell said the nabisco bonds suffered from the demise of 
junkbond pioneer drexel burnham lambert inc the oncepowerful 
investment house that collapsed in february and has been in 
liquidation 
plunging prices forced managers of junk bond portfolios to sell 
some betterquality marketable securities such as rjr nabisco 
after drexel left the scene as the sole marketmaker in a number of 
lowquality junk bonds 
the couldnt sell the real junk because there was no market 
but theres an actual market in rjr junk maxwell said 
