live cattle futures made record highs for the second straight 
day on the chicago mercantile exchange amid perceptions of tight 
nearterm supplies and reports of spot cattle prices as high as 82 
cents a pound in the texas panhandle 
analysts said the record prices reflect a seasonal peak in 
demand for beef and supply tightness stemming from delayed cattle 
marketings as a result of dry pasture conditions in the southern 
plains last fall and winter 
futures prices are lower than spot prices prompting some 
packers to turn to the futures market for deliveries which is also 
boosting prices said philip stanley a trader and consultant for 
dec futures inc in lincoln neb 
on any sign of weakness in the cash market youll probably see 
some pretty active selling come into the futures even with the 
discounts on the board tanley said 
live cattle futures settled 27 cent lower to 05 cent higher 
with the april contract which traded up to a record 8047 cents 
ending at 8042 cents a pound feeder cattle were 13 cent lower to 
22 cent higher with april at 84 cents a pound live hogs were 15 
cent to 50 cent higher with april at 5617 cents a pound frozen 
pork bellies were 25 cent lower to 125 cents higher with may at 
5902 cents a pound 
soybean futures fell moderately on the chicago board of trade 
reflecting increasing harvest pressure from brazil while grain 
futures ended mixed in subdued preholiday trading 
wheat futures settled 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with may 
at 367 a bushel corn was 1 cents to 2 cents lower with may at 
269 a bushel oats were 1 cent to 1 cents lower with may at 
149 a bushel soybeans were 3 cents to 6 cents lower with may at 
586 a bushel 
on new yorks commodity exchange gold settled 130 to 160 
higher with april at 37590 a troy ounce silver was 4 cents lower 
across the board with may at 5108 a troy ounce 
