<TEXT>
southland corp said it will continue to lose 
money until 1993 even if debt holders agree to forego 16 billion 
in interest payments as part of a complex debt restructuring 
the owner of the 7eleven convenience store chain projected a 
small 38 million profit in 1993 if it can restructure its debts 
and use cash to revamp its stores 
the forecast was contained in a preliminary prospectus on the 
restructuring that the company issued wednesday 
the plan involves the restructuring of 18 billion in bonds and 
preferred stock and would require holders of those securities to 
forego 16 billion in interest payments due through 1997 it also 
calls for selling 75 percent of the company to japanese business 
partners 
the company is struggling because it took on about 49 billion 
in debt when the founding thompson family took southland private in 
1987 the company lost 13 billion last year 
the prospectus said southland expects to lose 156 million this 
year 61 million in 1991 and 9 million in 1992 capital 
investments in new stores should bring the company a 38 million 
profit in 1993 and a 67 million gain in 1994 
southland late last month announced plans to sell 75 percent of 
the company to its japanese partners itoyokado co ltd and 
7eleven japan co ltd in exchange for 400 million in badly 
needed cash 
bond holders are skeptical about the proposal which would give 
them a stake of about 10 percent the thompson family about 10 
percent and other common shareholders about 5 percent of the 
restructured company 
southland officials reiterated their belief that unless 
bondholders approve the restructuring cashflow problems would 
force the company to seek relief under the bankruptcy code 
the preliminary filing stated that southland plans to open 1814 
new stores and close 1724 others by the end of 1997 to compete 
with convenience store rivals southland opened 60 stores and 
closed 340 others in 1989 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

